<h1>Variables and Data Types</h1>

<p>To use a variable, you need to declare it (create it), and then you can initialize it (give it a starting value).</p>

<p>
<b>Declaring a variable</b><br />
<br />
<b>Declaring</b> a variable means creating a spot in memory to hold some information.  The pattern you use to declare a variable is: <pre>DataType variableName;</pre></b>
</p>

<p>
<b>DataType</b> is the <em>type of data</em> that your variable will hold.  Here are the most common data types:

<table>
  <tr><td>Data Type</td><td>What it means</td><td>Example</td></tr>  
  <tr><td>int</td><td>integer</td><td><code>int a = 5;</code></td></tr>
  <tr><td>double</td><td>number with a decimal part (real number)</td><td><code>double b = 3.14159;</code></td></tr>
  <tr><td>String</td><td>text data</td><td><code>double name = "Winter Featherbottom";</code></td></tr>
  <tr><td>boolean</td><td>true or false</td><td><code>boolean userLoggedIn = false;</code></td></tr>
</table>

</p>

<p>
<b>Initializing a variable</b><br />
After you have declared the variable you can assign it a value: <pre>variableName = expression;</pre>
The expression on the other side of the equals sign can be any mathematical expression, or any other java code which yields a value.  For example:

<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
  int base = 3, height = 4;
  double area = 0.5 * base * height;     // area of a triangle
</pre>

</p>

<p>Here are several examples that illustrate different ways you can declare and initialize variables</p>

<pre class="prettyprint linenums">
  public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int a;        // declare a as an integer
        int b, c, d;  // declare three integer variables on the same line

        a = 5;        // assign 5 to a
        b = 2*a + 5;  // assign the result of '2*a + 5' to b.  b is now 15.

        int f = 5, g = 3;  // you can declare and assign multiple variables on the same line.
        int a;             // this is an error!  a is already declared on line 4!

        int b = 2.3;       // this is an error!  you can't assign 2.3 to b, because b can only hold an int!

        String name = "Marl Babok";  // declare an initialize name to be "Marl Babok"
        char letter = 'b';           // declare and initialize letter to be 'b'
        double pi = 3.14159;
    }
}
</pre>

